				\begin{document}$$J	=\left[\frac{e{D}_{0}}{{\tau }_{{\rm{i}}}}{({k}_{{\rm{B}}}T)}^{2}\left(\frac{e{\varnothing }_{{\rm{b}}}}{{k}_{{\rm{B}}}T}+1\right)\right]\exp \left(-\sqrt{\chi }\delta -\frac{e{\varnothing }_{{\rm{b}}}}{{k}_{{\rm{B}}}T}\right)\\ 	\times \left[\exp \left(\frac{e(V-I{R}_{{\rm{s}}})}{\eta {k}_{{\rm{B}}}T}\right)-1\right],$$\end{document}where e being the elementary charge, D0 = 2/[π(ħνF)2] the density of states of graphene, ħ the reduced Planck’s constant, νF the Fermi velocity in graphene, τi−1 represents the injection rate of carriers from the silicon contact to graphene, and is related to the silicon-graphene and metal-graphene coupling energy. kB the Boltzmann constant, T the absolute temperature, Øb being the Schottky barrier, χ the average barrier height, δ the oxide thickness, V the voltage applied across the diode, Rs the series resistance and η the ideality factor. The ideality factor η and Schottky barrier Øb can be extracted from the forward J–V characteristics. Through fitting the formula (1), values of η, Øb and τi are extracted to be 1.2, 0.7 eV, and 2.4 × 10−11 s, respectively, suggesting the good quality of Gr/Si Schottky junction. We did not use the effective Richardson constant to describe the Gr/Si Schottky junction, because the traditional Richardson constant A* overestimates the thermionic dark current of graphene/silicon Schottky junction without considering the finite density of states of graphene, which should be better accounted by using the Landauer formula.Fig. 2
